<br>
That has been my exact theme here.<br>
<br>
But even an alternate (&quot;contrafacual&quot; is the 'official' word for this) history has to have some basis in reality, and as I have made clear, the ONLY point at which Germany might conceivably have won the war was at the fall of France in 1940. From there on in it becomes more and more impossible. <br>
<br>
In the words of Churchill after the French collapse, and when it had become clear that Hitler did not intend to stop at that point, and just before the Battle of Britain began in ernest, &quot;Hitler knows he has to defeat us in this island or lose the war.&quot; Never were truer words spoken.<br>
<br>
After 1940, British defenses quickly grew to such a point that a German invasion became more and more impossible to contemplate. In that situation, US intervention (with or without Pearl Harbor) would eventually have become inevitable (for a large number of reasons there is not enough space to list here) and hence ultimate German defeat had to follow eventually.<br>
<br>
Thus: German victory has a direct bearing on the future of space and atomic development in such a world, and as I have tried to demonstrate, it is most likely that both would in fact have been much further BEHIND where they are today, and most definately not ahead as many people fondly imagine.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/03 1:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=46>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nazi Germany</span><hr size=1> I agree that the events of the spring to summer of 1940 were critical.  Here's the only possibility the Germans had of winning:<br>
<br>
The German panzer thrust around the south side of the allied armies in May 1940 stopped short of Dunkirk because Hitler and some of his generals were afraid of pushing too far ahead - they believed that the Brits and French had more fight left in them than they did.  If those tanks had gotten up the coast and cut the allied armies off from the Channel coast, the entire force probably would have been lost.  This would have entailed the loss of somewhere around 200 000 to 250 000 British soldiers and around 100 000 French soldiers who formed the core of much of the later British army and the Free French later on.<br>
<br>
In July-August 1940 the British had very little heavy equipment, but they did have a few hundred thousand men with rifles, which was a relatively formidable force since the Germans did not have proper sea transportation.  Without the men saved at Dunkirk there would simply have been more holes in Britain's shoreline defences than anything else.<br>
<br>
Next, the Germans would have had to have grasped the importance of radar and continued to strike the British radar stations as they did in the first few days of the battle of Britain.<br>
<br>
The next difference would have to be that the Germans would stick to their first policy of attacking the RAF airfields and fighter formations directly, instead of switching to bombing cities which forced the Luftwaffe fighters into a close support role for the bombers and allowed the British airfields to function with relatively little harassment.<br>
<br>
By launching concerted attack on the airfields and radar stations the RAF could probably have been broken.  With no air cover, the Royal Navy would have been unable to operate in the channel.  Most of the ships - Dutch barges and so on - which the Germans started to round up for an invasion of Britain would not have been very seaworthy on the unpredictable English Channel.  However, even a relatively weak German force landed by what effective ships the Germans did have, along with paratroopers dropped from planes, would under these circumstances have been able to establish a bridgehead in Britain, slowly build up, and probably fight their way northwards and take London and central England.<br>
<br>
The Germans would then have probably installed a government of German sympathizers in London (including former British cabinet ministers and aristocrats).  Churchill's government would probably have refused to give up and would have retreated to Wales or Scotland, perhaps from there on to Canada.  The result wold have been that the British Empire would have broken down into a civil war, probably with India and Pakistan declaring independence and falling on each other, and the Japanese wiping out the remainder of the empire in Asia as actually happened anyway.<br>
<br>
However, the Germans would have had to play a perfect campaign to achieve the above results - which is virtually impossible in military history (it might be said that Alexander played a perfect campaign against the Persians, but that's about it).<br>
<br>
The best chance for the Axis to defeat Soviet Russia would have been for the Japanese to attack the Russians in Siberia, thus creating a two-front war for the Soviets.  Judging from their later disaster against the Russians in 1945, the Japanese would probably not have made much headway, but the would have tied down Russia's Siberian divisions (the eastern border of Siberia was stripped bear of forces in 1941-1942).  This would have eliminated the only reserve the Russians had to launch their counter-attack during the battle of Moscow.<br>
<br>
However, even without the Soviet counter-attack at Moscow, the German army there might have succeeded in dying in the field because they were not equipped in any way for the conditions of the Russian winter.  This was because Hitler believed that the war in Russia would be over before winter.<br>
<br>
So, the Germans would also have had to have the foresight to realize that the Russians might hold out until winter, and provide stores of winter equipment as a contingency.  If they had done that, and the Japanese had tied down the Siberian divisions, then the Germans would probably have taken Moscow.<br>
<br>
Once again it requires an almost perfect campaign plan and perfect diplomatic ties between Germany and Japan.<br>
<br>
The question then remains of whether Germany &quot;winning&quot; WWII would have also meant the Germans successfully conquering the United States.  Even with Russia and Britain defeated, I do not see a German invasion of the United States as a feasible proposition.  The result wold have been an extended phony war or cold war between the axis and the U.S., not dissimilar to the Cold War that happened between the U.S. alliance and the Soviet block in the history that we know.  Given Nazi Germany's tendency to not commit itself to new technologies until faced with crisis, the Germans would probably have not woken up and put sufficient funding into ballistic missiles etc. until the Americans already had them well underway, even though the Germans would still have had Von Braun.<br>
<br>
Would America have taken the Nazis out with preemptive atomic missile attacks? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1280<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/03 7:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nazi Germany</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The best chance for the Axis to defeat Soviet Russia would have been for the Japanese to attack the Russians in Siberia, thus creating a two-front war for the Soviets. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
